The Bauchi State government has suspended the planned salary deductions to tame the spread of coronavirus in the state. Governor Bala Mohammed had directed the state accountant-general to suspend the deductions with immediate effect. The governor gave the order on Tuesday at the inauguration of the COVID-19 Economic Recovery Committee in Bauchi. LEADERSHIP had reported how the Nigeria Labour Congress (NLC)  and the state government came under severe criticism from workers in the state over the planned deductions. In a statement issued by Lawal Mu’azu, the Governor’s Special Assistant on new media, Bala Mohammed said the directive followed series of complaints by some civil servants in the state on the planned deductions. “I was told by the Head of Civil Service and the Organized Labour in the state that workers will contribute percentage from their salaries to support our campaign against the spread of coronovirus, but later, some workers complained that the government forced them into making the contribution. “With this development, I have directed the Accountant General and the Head of Civil Service to stop deduction of any amount from the salaries of workers, whoever wants to contribute as part of corporate social responsibility can meet the State Task Force.” The governor therefore acknowledged the sacrifices and contributions from some citizens in the ongoing campaign against coronavirus, assuring that his administration will not force any of them to make compulsory contribution.